nd the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Ethics Misconduct Malfeasance</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mar-a-Lago</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">live-detached</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/04/27/business/00-trump-memecoin/00-trump-memecoin-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Tim Enthoven</media:credit></media:content></item><item><title>Microsoft and OpenAI Loosen Their Partnership</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/27/technology/microsoft-openai-partnership.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/27/technology/microsoft-openai-partnership.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/27/technology/microsoft-openai-partnership.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Microsoft, OpenAI’s biggest financial partner, will continue to license the start-up’s technology but will no longer be its exclusive licensee.</description><dc:creator>Cade Metz and Karen Weise</dc:creator><pubDate>Mon, 27 Apr 2026 13:48:54 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Startup</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Microsoft</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2025/09/11/multimedia/27BIZ-MICROSOFT-OPENAI/11BIZ-OPENAI-1-qwbf-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:cre